snippet.textDisplay:
Btw Chrome has multiple developer channels.

When something is changed it goes to Canary, then after some testing it moves on to Dev for more testing. If the change is still working it moves to Beta to be heavily tested on everyday use. Once that has passed many months of testing and is extremely stable/failproof it moves on to the Stable version of Chrome.

Chrome Stable - Stable version of Chrome, most popular, receives major updates every 6 months
Chrome Beta - Pretty stable, might be a little rough around the edges and you may experience minor bugs/errors, but you can use new features before they hit the Stable channel.
Chrome Dev: New features of Chrome with little testing. This channel will be rough around the edges and you will encounter bugs and errors. Pretty much as soon as a new feature comes out it comes to here. Updates every 6 days (I believe)
Chrome Canary: The most unstable Chrome channel, multiple versions released every hour. No testing has been done on these versions and are extremely experimental. As soon as someone develops a new feature/bug fix etc: it goes to Chrome Canary.
